Integration tests for ctx-scan's summarize/hash/check/update pipeline, exercising the complete workflow in isolation with fake and real filesystems. Tests verify stale-detection, artifact generation, hash integrity, and orphan cleanup.

The file uses `FakeFs` (a `BTreeMap`-backed `Fs` impl from common) for hermetic tests and `StdFs` for tests that need real tempdir isolation. All tests share a constant `MODELS` bundle (`claude-sonnet-5` for both leaf and rollup); the actual LLM responses are mocked by `recording()`, which tracks call counts without making network requests.

Key invariants: `summarize()` writes leaf contexts to `.context/<path>.ctx`, a rollup, and a README in one go, respecting the scope gate (`MAX_TARGETS`) unless `approved=true` is passed. `check_run()` reports stale dirs, changed files, and missing artifacts as three separate collections—a file edit marks only its leaf and ancestor dirs stale, never siblings. `update_run()` regenerates only stale summaries (verified by comparing agent call counts across cycles) and deletes orphan leaves when source files are removed. `hash::store()` and `hash::compute()` persist and load `.context/hashes.json` to track freshness; hashes alone can be clean while summaries are missing (the "finding #11" bug this test documents).

`is_ignored()` respects `.ctxignore` patterns and builtin defaults (`target/`, `gen/`) without requiring a git repo. Fixtures are cleaned up with `drop(std::fs::remove_dir_all())` after each test to avoid pollution in `/tmp`.